                <head>383. Editorial Note</head>
                <p>As part of a general visit to five South American countries, Assistant Secretary
                        <persName corresp="#p_HHF1">Holland</persName> and <persName
                        corresp="#p_WSC1">Samuel C. Waugh</persName>, President of the Export-Import
                    Bank, visited Chile November 25–27. In a memorandum of December 12 by <persName
                        corresp="#p_HHF1">Holland</persName>, commenting on the trip, he stated in
                    part: “We emphasized to the Minister of Economy and Finance and other Ministers
                    that Chile must prepare a coordinated program for combating inflation, one that
                    has the approval of all responsible areas of the Government, and the Klein–Saks
                    Mission should submit the program to the United States. We would then be in a
                    position to indicate what type of aid the United States might be able to afford
                    in coordination with such a program.” (Department of State, Central Files,
                    110.15–HO/12–1255) In despatch 416 from <persName corresp="#p_RSI1"
                        >Santiago</persName>, December <pb facs="0830" n="796" xml:id="pg_796"/> 7,
                    “Principal Impressions Left as a Result of <persName corresp="#p_HHF1"
                        >Holland</persName>–<persName corresp="#p_WSC1">Waugh</persName> Visit,” the
                    Embassy offered its analysis of the trip. (<hi rend="italic">Ibid.,</hi>
                    033.1120/12–755)</p>
            </div>
